      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why W-Words Are Reliable in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>W is arguably the most playable of the 4-point tiles. While V and Y can be awkward, W flows naturally into English word patterns. The WH- opening alone covers hundreds of words (WHAT, WHICH, WHACK, WHISK, WIZARD). This versatility means you'll rarely be stuck with W on your rack for long.</p>
      <p>W also benefits from strong pairing potential. WAX words leverage the X tile, WIZ words leverage Z, and WH words combine W with the common H tile. The result is consistent mid-to-high scoring plays throughout the game.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing W-Words</h2>
      <p>Maximise your W-word scoring with these approaches:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>WH- is your bread and butter:</strong> WHACK (17 pts), WHISK (15 pts), WHISKY (19 pts) — the WH combination unlocks consistent high scores because H is common and W+H together cover premium squares easily.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Pair W with X for power plays:</strong> WAX (13 pts), WAXY (17 pts), WAXEN (15 pts), WAXWORK (24 pts) — the W+X combination produces some of the highest base scores on this list.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Use WE and WO for parallel plays:</strong> Unlike V, W has two-letter words. Place W above or below an existing word to form WE or WO while scoring your main word simultaneously.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>WR- words for tight spots:</strong> WRIST, WROTE, WRACK, WRAITH — the silent W in WR- words means these are often overlooked by opponents, leaving board positions open for you.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Don't overthink it:</strong> W is one of the easiest premium tiles to play. If you have a 12+ point W-word available, take it rather than holding for a perfect setup.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">W Compared to Other 4-Point Tiles</h2>
      <p>W, V, F, H, and Y are all worth 4 points, but they play very differently:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>W vs V:</strong> W has two-letter words (WE, WO) while V has none — making W far easier to play in tight positions</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>W vs Y:</strong> Both are flexible, but W produces higher average scores thanks to WH- and WAX- combinations</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>W vs H:</strong> H is more common (2 tiles) but W's built-in 4 points mean every W-word outscores the equivalent H-word by 3 points</span></li>
      </ul>

